      <h2>The DOSH Reality: Compliance is Not Optional</h2>

      <p>It's 8 AM on a Tuesday. DOSH inspectors arrive at your warehouse. They check your forklift documentation. One forklift lacks current FMI certification. Another hasn't been inspected in 18 months. A third shows no evidence of operator training records.</p>

      <p>The result? Immediate stop-work order. RM50,000 fine. Operations shut down for 2 weeks. Lost revenue: RM200,000. Client relationships damaged.</p>

      <p>This scenario plays out across Malaysia weekly. DOSH (Department of Occupational Safety and Health) regulations for forklift operations are strict—and enforcement is increasing.</p>

      <h2>What is DOSH and Why Does It Matter?</h2>

      <p>DOSH is Malaysia's occupational safety authority under the Ministry of Human Resources. For forklift operations, DOSH enforces:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Occupational Safety and Health Act 1994 (OSHA)</strong> – Primary legislation governing workplace safety</li>
        <li><strong>Forklift and Industrial Truck Regulations</strong> – Specific rules for forklift operations</li>
        <li><strong>FMI (Factories and Machinery Act 1967)</strong> – Equipment certification requirements</li>
      </ul>

      <p><strong>Key Point:</strong> DOSH regulations apply to ALL forklift operations in Malaysia:
      <br>• Warehouses and distribution centers
      <br>• Construction sites
      <br>• Manufacturing facilities
      <br>• Ports and logistics hubs</p>

      <p>Exemptions exist only for specific agricultural applications with limited use.</p>

      <h2>2024 DOSH Forklift Requirements: What You Must Know</h2>

      <h3>1. FMI Registration and Certification</h3>

      <p><strong>Requirement:</strong> All forklifts must be registered with DOSH and display a valid FMI (Factories and Machinery) registration number.</p>

      <p><strong>Process:</strong>
      <br>• Registration before operation (new forklifts)
      <br>• Inspection and certification by DOSH-approved inspector
      <br>• Issuance of FMI plate/certificate</p>

      <p><strong>Validity:</strong>
      <br>• New forklifts: Certification valid for 1 year initially
      <br>• Subsequent certifications: Valid for 2-3 years depending on usage and condition
      <br>• Inspection required: Every 12-24 months</p>

      <h3>2. Operator Training and Licensing</h3>

      <p><strong>Requirement:</strong> All forklift operators must complete DOSH-recognized training and hold valid certification.</p>

      <p><strong>Training Components:</strong>
      <br>• Classroom theory (safety regulations, load calculations, hazard recognition)
      <br>• Practical operation (driving, lifting, stacking, emergency procedures)
      <br>• Written and practical examinations</p>

      <p><strong>License Validity:</strong>
      <br>• Forklift operator license: Valid for 3 years
      <br>• Refresher training: Required after accidents or near-misses
      <br>• Renewal: Requires re-examination</p>

      <h3>3. Equipment Safety Features</h3>

      <p><strong>Mandatory Features (2024 Standards):</strong>
      <br>• Overhead guard (protection from falling objects)
      <br>• Seatbelt (operator restraint system)
      <br>• Backup alarm (audible warning when reversing)
      <br>• Warning lights (flashing lights during operation)
      <br>• Load rating plate (clearly visible capacity information)
      <br>• Horn (audible warning device)
      <br>• Fire extinguisher (minimum 2kg ABC rating)</p>

      <h3>4. Maintenance and Inspection Records</h3>

      <p><strong>Requirement:</strong> Forklifts must undergo regular maintenance with documented records.</p>

      <p><strong>Inspection Schedule:</strong>
      <br>• Daily: Pre-shift inspection by operator (checklist required)
      <br>• Monthly: Basic maintenance by qualified mechanic
      <br>• Annually: Comprehensive inspection by DOSH-approved inspector</p>

      <p><strong>Documentation:</strong>
      <br>• Maintenance logbook (all repairs and servicing recorded)
      <br>• Inspection certificates (current FMI certificate displayed)
      <br>• Operator training records (available for DOSH review)</p>

      <h3>5. Workplace Safety Requirements</h3>

      <p><strong>Forklift Operating Areas Must Have:</strong>
      <br>• Designated travel paths (marked lanes)
      <br>• Speed limit signs (typically 15 km/h for forklifts)
      <br>• Pedestrian separation (barriers or marked walkways)
      <br>• Adequate lighting (minimum 200 lux for driving areas)
      <br>• Floor load capacity rating (supports forklift + maximum load)</p>

      <h2>The Cost of Non-Compliance: What Violations Really Cost</h2>

      <h3>Fine Schedule (2024)</h3>

      <p><strong>Unregistered Forklift (No FMI):</strong> RM10,000 - RM50,000 per forklift
      <br><strong>Uncertified Operator:</strong> RM5,000 - RM20,000 per operator
      <br><strong>Expired Certification:</strong> RM5,000 - RM15,000 per forklift
      <br><strong>No Safety Features (missing backup alarm, seatbelt, etc.):</strong> RM2,000 - RM10,000 per violation
      <br><strong>No Maintenance Records:</strong> RM3,000 - RM10,000
      <br><strong>Workplace Safety Violations:</strong> RM5,000 - RM30,000</p>

      <h3>Operational Costs</h3>

      <p><strong>Beyond Fines:</strong>
      <br>• Stop-work orders (operations halt until violations corrected)
      <br>• Equipment seizure (non-compliant forklifts impounded)
      <br>• Business license suspension (repeat violations)
      <br>• Legal liability (accidents involving non-compliant equipment = gross negligence)
      <br>• Insurance claim denial (non-compliance voids coverage)</p>

